---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleScenario from "../../../components/module/ModuleScenario.astro";
import ModuleFlowDiagram from "../../../components/module/ModuleFlowDiagram.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleRecap from "../../../components/module/ModuleRecap.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "25-serving";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="25 · Serving a RAG API">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Everything so far — ingestion, chunking, embeddings — happens offline, once per document. This module
        wires the online path: what happens the instant a user asks a question. This is the module where the
        pipeline becomes a product.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <ModuleScenario moduleId={moduleId} />

    <ModuleFlowDiagram moduleId={moduleId} />

    <h2>The request path</h2>
    <p>
      Four steps, in order: <strong>embed</strong> the incoming question with the same model used in Module 20,
      <strong>retrieve</strong> the nearest chunks from the vector index, <strong>construct a prompt</strong> that
      includes the question plus the retrieved chunks (with enough structure that the model can cite which chunk
      supports which claim), and <strong>call the LLM</strong> — a fast model by default, escalating to a reasoning
      model only when the task calls for it (Module 75 covers that trade-off in cost terms).
    </p>

    <h2>Citations aren't optional</h2>
    <p>
      A RAG answer without a citation back to its source chunk is a claim you can't verify and a user can't trust.
      Return the chunk ID (or document + offset) alongside every answer — it costs nothing extra since retrieval
      already has that metadata, and it's the difference between "an AI said so" and "here's the paragraph it came
      from."
    </p>

    <h2>Handling "I don't know"</h2>
    <p>
      When retrieval returns nothing relevant, the right answer is for the model to say so — not to answer from
      general knowledge as if it had a source. A simple guard: if the top retrieved chunk's similarity score is
      below a threshold, skip the LLM call for that context entirely and return a plain "not found in the indexed
      documents" response.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>No citation in the response — makes every answer unverifiable and erodes trust the moment it's wrong once.</li>
      <li>Letting the model answer when retrieval found nothing relevant — this is where hallucination gets blamed on "the AI" when it's actually a missing guard.</li>
      <li>Skipping request logging at launch "to add later" — Module 30's event log needs data from day one, and you can't retroactively log a request that already happened.</li>
      <li>Defaulting to the most expensive/slowest model for every query — start fast-tier, escalate only when needed.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleRecap moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
